Life insurance is a contract between an insurance policy holder and an insurer or assurer, where the insurer promises to pay a designated beneficiary a sum of money upon the death of an insured person. Depending on the contract, other events such as terminal illness or critical illness can also trigger payment.

There are many types of life insurance and knowing which one is the best for you is crucial.

The basics on understanding factors in life insurance are simple:

Policy length: How long the insurance lasts
Cash value: If an insurance plan has cash value, then it lasts until your death if you consistently pay your premium.
Premiums: The premium is the amount of money needed to pay every month/year/etc. The premium price for your insurance depends on your plan.
Death benefit: A death benefit is a payout to the receiver of a life insurance policy, annuity, or pension when the insured or annuitant dies. Life Insurance

Medigap is Medicare Supplement Insurance that helps fill "gaps" in Original Medicare and is sold by private companies. Original Medicare pays for much, but not all, of the cost for covered health care services and supplies. A Medicare Supplement Insurance (Medigap) policy can help pay some of the remaining health care costs, like: Copayments, Coinsurance, and Deductibles. Medicare Supplement Insurance
A Medicare Advantage is another way to get your Medicare Part A and Part B coverage. Medicare Advantage Plans, sometimes called "Part C" or "MA Plans," are offered by Medicare-approved private companies that must follow rules set by Medicare. If you join a Medicare Advantage Plan, you'll still have Medicare but you'll get most of your Part A and Part B coverage from your Medicare Advantage Plan, not Original Medicare. Medicare Advantage Plans
Medicare Part D, also called the Medicare prescription drug benefit, is an optional United States federal-government program to help Medicare beneficiaries pay for self-administered prescription drugs. Part D Plans
Long-term care insurance policies reimburse policyholders a daily amount (up to a preselected limit) for services to assist them with activities of daily living such as bathing, dressing, or eating. You can select a range of care options and benefits that allow you to get the services you need, where you need them. Long-Term Care
A cancer insurance policy is an insurance policy that pays a lump sum if the policy holder is diagnosed with cancer. These plans have payouts that typically range from $5,000 to $200,000 (plans with higher payouts have higher premiums). Cancer Insurance Policy
Short term disability insurance typically starts paying benefits within two weeks of a qualifying illness or injury and covers you for a benefit period that’s usually between 13-26 weeks. You’ll continue to receive benefits until you’re able to return to work or until you reach the end of your benefit period. Short-Term Disability
Long-Term Disability (LTD) insurance is private insurance that helps people who can't work because of a disability. If you have LTD insurance, it will replace some of the income you lose when you can't work because of a disability. Long-Term Disability
Dental insurance is a form of health insurance designed to pay a portion of the costs associated with dental care. Dental
Vision care insurance will often cover routine eye health expenses such as eye exams, contact lens fittings, contact lenses, and eyeglass lenses and frames. Some plans may even provide a discount on LASIK procedures and other corrective surgeries. Vision

Before applying for social security, you must be deemed eligible. You can apply in your home country before coming to the United States when filing an application for an immigrant visa with the U.S. Department of State. In most cases, if you apply for an SSN and card with your immigrant visa application, you don’t have to visit a Social Security office in the United States. If you are lawfully present in the United States, you must contact your local Social Security office. See the section below for what you need to submit to the Social Security office.

If you are undocumented, you will most likely be unable to receive these benefits unless you qualify inside the category of the exception. (You’ve worked for 40 quarters in the United States, you are in the Armed Forces, you are disabled, etc).

For more information, refer to the official website of the Social Security Administration. Eligibility and How to Apply for Social Security and Social Security #/Card
